{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_doyle_ver01/data/sn86091100/00415666172/1914022601/0847.xml":{"full_text":"EDITORIAL PAGE OF THE FREE PRESS\nIDAHO COUNTY FREE PRE^S\nHAROLD HARRIS, Local Editor.\nL. A. WISENER, Editor and Proprietor.\nGRANGEVILLE, IDAHO, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 26,1914\nTHE PANAMA TOLLS.\n\"The canal shall be free and open to the vessels of ali\nnations on terms of entire equality, so that there shall\nbe no discrimination in respect to the charges\nof traffic.\" So runs Rule 1 of the Hay-Paunsefote Treaty. And\nit is a highly creditable feeling on the part of many Amer cans,\nreflected by President Wilson, that we cannot afford to be un\nfair or unfaithful to our promises simply because we happen to\nbe strong.\nVolumes have been published about this matter of tolls\nthrough the Panama Canal, but the biggest book would be the\none containing what people don't know about it. We afe be\nginning to suspect, at least, that the country generally will not\nprofit by the free-passage provisions of the law signed bk Mr.\nTaft under exceptional conditions, and that the exemptions in\nfavor of our coastwise traffic will serce only to take expenses\noff the shoulders of the American shipping combine. This trust\nis based largely on a monopoly of wharfage and steel mills and\nbased largely on a monopoly of wharfage and steel mills and\nshipbuilding. With free steel, free ore, and the. wharf-bu lding\nactivity of cities like New York, Boston, and the Pacific ports,\ncompetition may spring up in our coastwise trade, giving\nsumers, sooner or later, the benefits of a free canal,\nthings stand, the trust will get the benefit of free passagf, and\nthe United States will only operate a cheap waterway for the\ngreat captains of industry to make money by. This is probably\nthe President 's view\u2014part of it.\nThe whole floe-tolls proposition is as impolitic as it is\nscaly. We have more to ask of Great Britian in the way of un\nrestricted navigation of our intercommunicating waterways\nthan she has to ask ot us at Panama. Canada is about t<J build\nthe Georgian Bay Ship Canal from French River to the Ottawa,\ntwenty-five feet deep and capacious enough to carry the great\nest lake freighters or standard ocean-going tramps. This sys\ntem will flank our whole lake and interior basin commerce. The\nErie Barge Canal is a tadpole ditch compared with it. Ships\nsailing from Chicago, Milwaukee, Duluth or West Superipr will\nbe able, to reach the ocean via Montreal by this route, and that\ntoo without breaking bulk on the mileage it would take to reach\nErie, Pa., by the present route. Canada will then command a\ncommerce far more important to us than that of the Panama\nCanal. She will have the whip hand of us to an extent qhite as\ngreat as that which we can get on Great Britain by wrendhing\ntreaty from its plain meaning. And she will be able to say:\nYou made a treaty agreeing to let the ships of all h\u00e2tions\nthrough the Panama Canal on equal terms. You broke that\ntreaty by letting your own coastwise ships through free jind\nfusing the same treatment to our coastwise ships. Noy we'll\nuse our advantage in the Great Lakes outlet!\" Our treaty as\nto the Great Lakes passages is that they shall be open, to the\nshipping of both nations on equal terms. But what will that\nmean once we begin playing fast and loose with the words\nequal terms?\"\nWe are wrong in this matter and the\ncon\nBut, as\na\nI i\nre\non\n_ sooner we get right\ntlm better. We are. wrong, not only as regards Great Britain\nand our relations with Mexico, Colombia (both a Pacific and an\nAtlantic power), and Canada, but also with Germany, France,\nand Portugal. We are wrong with the whole, world. Our case\nis like that of the private citizen who had done somethihg that\nwas denounced as criminal. \"Creeminal!\" repeated a French\nwoman. \"Creeminal! Eet is vorse zan creeminal.\nEet is\npositively silly!\nFalseness to obligations,\nging attitude toward them\nprecedents.\n9 9\nor a squirmy, wriggling, pbttifog\nour part, cannot be justified by\nIf England drove a sharp bargain with us long\nynars ago, that is (to-day) neither here nor there. A bargain.\nWe are too big to welch. Moreover\u2014and therfore\u2014the coun\ntry should support the president in his determination tq repeal\nthe controverted Panama-tolls arrangement. The Adamson\njoint resolution should be passed by congress\u2014and passed now\n\u2014Collier's.\non\n\n\nv\u00bbvi)nin mu B __\nT)i f E PRESIDENT BUSY.\naCt J bat who !0m *0 Washington ever see the\nl them ,0 tblnlt tllat l,e is an inaccessible\nperson, like a king or emperor. The contrary is true. The\nhis Situation* hiit* 1 Vof CCC8 Rible |w r?\" im \"S inabla f one in\nFlr \u00ef i h ,s uot accessible to the general i public,\nT nT '\"'\"I 0D,slde of ,lis \u00bbWh family, dois so by\nfs a reln '\"'\u00bb\"'\"'\"'\"\"s are not hard to make if there\nminute^andT\"^\"/' i,lto four and five\n,ld d ri \"S 'T ke\none \u00aboldoct to -.'\u201eother 4^-.Sv Ti PI S rr m\nbefore, and Irvin\u00bb to auuh TIT f\u2122\n\u2022Brm.f. a1 iiuu ox parte statements yi tlieir i\ne r grievances and their advice. It is in the litter re\ngard that Ih-esident Wilson is stronger than his predecessors.\nresident Taft saw a great many people, but, as lie bad I\nwhi wl \"\u00b0i h 1S pro ram dail went to smash. People\neeedinwrV or h 'I e mmu es stayed an hour and the sue\nwork M t-T nS l nt ott President Roosevelt was a terror for\nrhat Wi Wa te tlc t0 but 11 is the general opinion\nmore wrkK T P^sical endurances, gets tl, rough with\ncXr^T\" h e Ueve r talks Roosevelt would harangue\nus \u00b0P imons before they were asked, and usual]\u00bb r\nHe had 1 %Tl ent 0f hi cal,ers befor a 11 was cojnpleted.\nHe had a method, however. He was forever on the watch for\nDiggers in the wood P lle and usually assumed an air of hrus\nBuTroo^vcU 0n< th i e Calier S sineerit y in his own proposals.\nK- rf WaS word any'conscientiou.s\n1\nman. He never changed his opinion unless he felt that his\npromise was wrong or unwise or hastily given. Then he was\nready to take all responsibilty for having made a mistake and\ncorrect it.\nThere is no impulse about President Wilson. A cooler\nman never stepped into the White House, He can not be rush\ned. He is as impassive as a judge on the bench when anybody\ncomes to him. But he isa marvelously good listener. In this\nrespect he beats both his predecessors, for he listens both with\near and the mind. His short, sharp, interjected questions are.\nalways to the. point and show that he is carrying the whole con\nversation with him. When the callers go away they know no\nmore about what the president thinks than when they came.\nBut they soon learn. Prompt decision is the president's favo\nrite attitude. He likes to get a subject off his mind. He has\nno patience with dallying with a problem or shunting it to\nsomebody else when he knows it must finally come back to him.\nFrom rising until breakfast he is busy at the White House\nproper with letters that concern him personally. For the pur\npose of answering them, a stenographer has been summoned\nfrom the offices. At 10 o'clock the president, spruced up and\ndressed usually in a gray suit, with a small dark tie, goes to the\noffice through a passageway which also contains the White\nHouse laundry. His secretaries have preceded him and have\nmade a list of engagements for him.\nThe secretaries are allowed some leeway in making engage\nd ,W T\u00b0. r exa \"!R e senators and representatives are put\ndown for tune without previously consulting the president,\n1 hese appointments ordinarily are short, not over five minutes,\nI comment persons who come to pay their respect ore allowed a\nminute or two. Delegations can come only after the president\nhas been consulted. The list is made up days in advance of\ncourse, but on the morning of each day it is typewritten in full,\nlu the resi dent an ther stands l n se re\nhun ff in fit IV 1 \u00b0f m\u00ee \u00ee 10,1 Kl i f V\nhung in the outei office for the public to gaze at. Tuesdays and\nhn'engancmmits^' I Wcdnfi\u00abd^ he P res 'd ent makes few or no pub\nWod r CS,lay he re TT r few e a e\nments that may take a long time, say half an hour or an hour.\nto\nin\nis\na\nBUSINESS AWAKENING.\nOn every hand are indications that business is awakening.\nThat the night of business depression is past in the word that\nfrom nearly all the leading business concerns of the\ncomes\ncountry.\nIt began with the renewed energy in the New England\nmanufactories noted in these, columns a few days ago. It is\ngradually spreading over the land.\nOne of the members of a leading publishing firm told an\nIdaho official recently in San Francisco that a single railroad\nwith headquarters at Pittsburg had given an order for the ex\npenditure of $12,000,000 for new machinery and improvements.\nThe president of a wholesale paint and varnish company\nwith headquarters at Chicago, reperesenting a capital of $15,\n000,000, lias inaugurated an advance movement all along the\nline and speaks optimistically of the business outlook of the\ncountry generally.\nHere in Idaho we will no doubt have an unusually good\nyear. Our crops are always good. There is a demand for our\nfruit and our wool and our cattle and hogs and mutton.\nThe Oregon Short Line will soon begin extensive improve\nments involving the outlay of a large sum.\nThe northwest is the first to feel business depression and\nthe last to get the impulse of a revival, but such revival\nnear at hand even in our section.\u2014Statesman.\na\na\nin\nseems\nPIGS IS PIGS BUT PORK VARIES.\nT heie is as much difference in hogs as there is in men. A\ngreat many persons think that a ham is a ham, no matter what\nsort of a hog it comes from, but those who know the packing\nbusiness realize the difference between hogs fed\nfoods.\non various\nI or instance, the Canadian porker, fattened upon peas,\nbarley and other hard grain products, makes a lean, compact,\nline-grained animal, which is entirely different from the\nfed P*\u00a3 of American side of the line.\nThe home of a Canadian hog, weighing eay fifteen pounds\nml1 have ten per cent less fat upon it and a^orresnondinvlv\n'\u00bbrger degree of lean than that of a hog fed in Iowa or Illinois\nupon corn exclusively\nThen, too, there is a decided difference in the grade of\ntexture of the animal. The expert can easily separate the \u00abner\nhams and bacons from the coaser grades\nThe mast-fed pig of the south-the'animal that lives on\nm al, even when the lat^U^niS^OTgrafo 1 d lry fed\ndayman knows little of these diZcnc.es, and to him\nward\" bl tie Th# is f| ick in from out\n1 np To\u00bbranre.s the different grades is a valuable man to the\ni packer wherever he mav be, and he can -ihv\ngood salary. V\n\nI fe ^rs. Roebuck Co., have just issued their animal state\neut nd declared a dividend of 21.17 per cent on their $40.000,\nof om J lon stock. The man who is afraid of robbing the\nmadorde houses of a living because they advertise their goods\ncbeap ha another fear coming. There are very few met\nm h ants r other tradesmen making 21 per cent profit anvwhere\nanother thing about this mail order concern as\nr 6 aS 8 otllers that were investigated last vear The i\nt,ffat,on sh< wed that among their 20.000 girls and young\nmen em Ployes, very few received more than from thr^ tn\nflVe dolla rs a week, and it is claimed as a result mmv in do\nparatioa are driven to white slavery. Patrons of these soulless\nco irib te to d\ndis A Nevad a, observes the Pocatello THbune\n\ncorn\niys command\non\nmves\nand\ntoe\nhis\nno\nto\nMoney isn't everything. But yon never go to a poor m.\nwhen you want advice.\nIt takes a great man to build an emipre or a railroad or\u00ab,\ninteroceanic canal. But it takes a greater man to keep the S\non his grouch when he gets up in the morning with a sea lionh\nhis mouth and finds that liis wife, is trying to crowd an enfo\na Chautauqua lecture course into the one hour before he I,a?!\nchance to beat it &S\nof Advice on matrimony and castor oil run as an entry\nEverybody wants to give it and nobody wants to take it\nMere man is getting less important every day. We sa\u00bb\nsix weddin S writeups in which the name of the groom has been\ne ft out altogether 2\nTruth crushe j to earth wi|1 rise (n A[|d\nround up a lie merely produces 10 more lies. 8\nChp*r nr\\i T j\nSAYS LUKE M'LUKE:\nHalf the world has an awful time trying to find out bn\nthe other half lives.\nWhen you start to show a man the error of his\npick out some guy you know you can lick.\nThe reason a woman knows she can pick out a good hus\nband for her daughter is because she selected a hunk of chepa\u00bb\nfor her daughter's father.\nWhn one man has a receipt for his pew rent and another\nman has the coupons for seats to see \"The Trail of Slime\"\nyou'll notice the crowd never follows the man with the\nrent receipt.\nMost women are so anxious to get married that they wj]j\ncheerfully hitch up with a man who has to borrow money to get\nthe marriage license. 8\nIt is a good scheme to look out for the future, but some men\nact as their own funeral directors before they are ready to die.\nPoliteness and charity should both begin at home. But\nthey never do.\nOnce in a while you will hear of a chorus girl who doesn't\nthink she, is better than the prima donna and you may also run\ninto a clerk who doesn't imagine that he knows more than the\nboss.\nways always\npe\u00bb\nIf every man has his price, there are some of them who\nlook as though they would fall for a counterfeit Mexican nickel\nMaybe Joah swallowed the whale and maybe a lot of other\nwonderful things happened, but ther never was a man who\ncould lose his.money and still retain friends.\nFather will kick if mother leaves a light burning in the\nkitchen when she isn't working there| But if daughter ist\nmember of the Hand Holders' union father wants a light in the\nfront room no matter how big the gas bills ge.t.\u2014Oincinnatti\nEnquirer.\nis\nFOREST FIRES WELL CONTROLLED.\nDuring 1913 the forces on the national forests fought\n4,250 fires, or nearly twice as many as started in 1912, the best\nyear the forests have ever had. Nothwithstanding the great\nincrease in the number of fires, Forester Graves considers that\nthe showing made by the forest service was quite as favorable\nas that in the preceding year, because the damage done and the\ncosts of fire fighting were no greater proportionately than ia\n1912. In both years practically 50 per cent of all fires were\ndetected and extinguished before they burned over a quarter of\nan acre, and 25 per cent of both years' fires were put out before\nthey covered 10 acres. Of last year's fires, 3,278, or consider\nably more than the whole number of fires in 1912, were con\nfined to areas of less than 10 acres, and in 1,080 additional\nfires less than $100 damage was done by each. In only 25 fires\ndid the damage amount to $1,000. The aggregate loss in tim\nber is estimated at nearly 59 million board feet, valued at about\n$8-,000, and the damage to young growth and forage is estimat\ned at about $110,000 making to total of about $192,000. About\n18 per cent of this loss, however, was incurred on private lands\nwithin the forests where 16 per cent of the fires had origin.\nThe anti-saloon contest in this state will make fat picking\nfor a journalist down in Ohio. He takes the cream off the con\ntributions of the faithful for from the first rush of money to the\n\u00efeague. treasury he will get his pound of flesh. It would be a\ngood idea to let that eastern journal do the fighting for state\nwide prohibition in this state. Those papers in Idaho that\ndevoted their services and their columns for the love of good\nmorals and right living have for their reward the conscience.of\na duty well and faithfully performed, while an eastern paper\nand prmt-shop organized by the league will feed on the cream j\not the shekels that will flow into its coffers. How delightfully I\nlovely!\u2014Idahoan.\nThe second annual Idaho County Horse Show, to be held\nin range.v iHe on May 28 and 29, is receiving support from all\nparts of the county. From the four corners comes words of en\ncouragement and promises of support. The show this year i\u00bb j\ngoing to do what last year's exhibition did-exceed\nmost sanguine hopes and prove a trump card for the livestock\nand agricultural interests of the county. Everybodv is invited\no end a hand\u2014-there's no speed limit on boosting a good tiling\nlike the horse show.\nthe\neven\nGra e y dle 1S entitled to some little distinction through\nthe tact that Bandit Lopez has not been sighted here yet. But\nmen, there are many towns in Austria which have the same call\non the rest of the world.\nIn case of fire, absence of body is sometimes better than\npresence of mind.\nDn t it about time to begin to win a\nbaseball pennant tld 3\nyear?\nSOMETHING TO FRET ABOUT.\nIn some parts of Africa the natives don't know how to\ntoe lioid 6 seems fe have almost everything but th*","height":"20568","width":"13800"}}
